outlooksByWeek.1: Missing time and missing the end zone held Adams back from the upper echelon of fantasy wideouts in 2019, but his volume and production were still there when he was healthy. His 17.7 points per game total was the second-best of his career and he's still Green Bay's best WR option heading into 2020. The Vikings were among the top-10 most-generous WR fantasy defenses a year ago, so lock in Adams with confidence for Week 1.
outlooksByWeek.2: Adams surprised no one by leading the Packers in targets, receptions and yards in Week 1, ending up as Aaron Rodgers' top target, just like he was for all of last season when healthy. This is the sort of output we should expect from Adams nearly every week and, with the Detroit secondary looking a bit banged up heading into Week 2, the Green Bay receiver is an easy pick as your WR1.
outlooksByWeek.3: Adams suffered a hamstring injury in Week 2 against the Lions, but it appears he avoided a serious setback and could be good to go for Week 3. Keep a close eye on his status, as that will be the only reason you'd keep him out of your fantasy lineup. The Saints were one of the weakest teams against wideouts last season (sixth-most fantasy points allowed to the position) so, despite a solid start to 2020, Adams would still be a must-play here if healthy.
outlooksByWeek.4: Adams has been dealing with a hamstring injury and tweeted this morning that he was not going to be on the field tonight.
outlooksByWeek.6: Keep a close eye on the injury reports this week, because a healthy Adams goes straight into all lineups. The Green Bay offense has been performing well with or without him this season, but he sees such incredible volume and will surely become the focal point of the team once again if he plays. Consider him a top-end WR1 against Tampa Bay, if healthy.
outlooksByWeek.7: Adams was back to seeing double-digit targets in his return to action in Week 6, and while the Packers did struggle mightily against the Buccaneers, it's a positive sign just to see Adams back to full volume. Against a much weaker Houston defense, he's back to being a must-start wideout in what should be a rebound performance for Aaron Rodgers and the Packers.
outlooksByWeek.8: The best receiver in fantasy football was definitely back in action in Week 7, racking up an incredible 196 yards and a pair of scores against a bottom-10 pass defense from Houston. He gets an even better matchup against Minnesota in Week 8 and, while a healthy Aaron Jones could slightly impact his ceiling, that's overthinking it to the highest degree. Adams is arguably the top option in all of fantasy for the week ahead and should start in all leagues.
outlooksByWeek.9: The reception and yardage totals weren't that impressive, but Adams hauled in a trio of TD passes in Week 8 to give him a massive fantasy stat line for the second week in a row. Healthy and back in the lineup since the bye week, Adams has seen double-digit targets in every start and will be even more important in Week 9 against an elite run defense from San Francisco. Look for Adams to be on the receiving end of plenty of Aaron Rodgers' passes, making him one of the top options in all of fantasy this week.
outlooksByWeek.10: Adams delivered a trademark outing against the 49ers in Week 9, racking up 173 yards and scoring a touchdown while logging 12 targets. When healthy this season, Adams has seen double-digit targets and lots of red zone looks. That should continue against one of the weaker pass defenses in the NFL (Jacksonville) in Week 10, when Adams will be a top fantasy wideout in all formats.
outlooksByWeek.11: Adams found the end zone for the fourth straight game in the Packers' Week 10 win over the Jaguars, catching eight passes for 66 yards (including that six-yard scoring strike). Next up is a Colts defense allowing the sixth-fewest WR fantasy points per game. Even so, Adams remains one of the top overall fantasy players and is always a "must start."
outlooksByWeek.12: Adams is one of the best receivers in the NFL and proves that on a weekly basis with incredible stat lines when healthy. Even against a very strong Indianapolis defense in Week 11, he went over 100 yards and found the end zone. The Bears are great against the pass, but nothing should stop you from putting a healthy Adams in your starting lineup.
outlooksByWeek.13: The Packers didn't need to pass the ball all that often iin order to put away the Bears in Week 12, but Adams did find the end zone before the game got too out of hand. That extending his scoring streak to six games and  he'll look to make it seven against the Eagles, a team that's solid against the pass but not too imposing of a matchup. Consider him a top-end WR1 in all leagues in Week 13.
outlooksByWeek.14: Since returning from injury in Week 6, Adams has scored 11 touchdowns over eight games, with 100-plus  yards in four of those contests. He's truly one of the best players in all of fantasy football and should remain locked into your lineups against a lackluster Detroit defense.
outlooksByWeek.15: There may not be a better fantasy player than Adams, who has scored a touchdown in eight straight games with five 100-yard performances over that span. Against a Carolina defense which allowed four passing touchdowns to the Broncos a week ago, lock in Adams as your top wideout and trust that yet another big performance is imminent.
outlooksByWeek.16: Adams did post a disappointing final line in Week 15 against the Panthers, but he still received 10 targets and hauled in seven catches. The Titans provide a much better matchup for opposing wideouts, and it is a perfect spot for a rebound performance from the elite receiver. Trust him as a top wideout in all fantasy formats.
outlooksByWeek.17: Adams made up for a lackluster Week 15 by scoring three times in Week 16's blowout win over the Titans. He's a superstar and a must-play in all formats, even against a much tougher Chicago defense in the 2020 finale.

player.seasonOutlook: Adams is back as Aaron Rodgers' unquestioned No. 1 target -- a role that has allowed him to post four consecutive seasons as a top-10 WR in fantasy points per game. Adams handled a career-high 31% target share and was fantasy's No. 2-scoring WR during the 12 weeks in which he was active last season. He finished as a top-five WR in 42% of those outings, which trailed only Michael Thomas. The only concern here is durability as Adams has missed at least one regular-season game due to injury in each of the past three seasons, including four 2019 absences. We'll need to dock him slightly for that, but the 27-year-old's massive usage locks him into the top-end WR1 mix.

outlooksByWeek.1: The Broncos were solid against the run last season in surrendering just 4.0 yards per carry to opposing backfields, but their front seven faces a serious challenge with the bruising Henry. Leading the league in rushing by nearly 200 yards last season and with some preseason talk of him getting more work as a receiver fuels RB1 status for Henry heading into this prime-time conference meeting.
outlooksByWeek.2: Delivering his league-leading seventh 100-yard rushing performance since the start of last season, Henry handled an astounding 34 touches in the rousing win over the Broncos this past Monday. The Jaguars coughed up gobs of scrimmage yardage to the Colts' backfield in Week 1, aiding Henry's case as arguably the best play at the position this week.
outlooksByWeek.3: Scoreless through two appearances despite gobs of touches, Henry's 84 rushing yards in Week 2 marked his fewest since Week 9 of last season. Due for some scoring success as the engine of the Tennessee ground game, Henry should thrive during a matchup with a Vikings defense allowing 140 rushing yards per game to backs this season.
outlooksByWeek.4: This week's game has been postponed and will be played later in the season.
outlooksByWeek.5: Henry has averaged nearly 30 touches per game as the offensive engine for Tennessee this season. The Bills have yielded the ninth-fewest fantasy points and just 83 rushing yards per game to backfields, and yet Henry's amazing workload supports RB1 expectations.
outlooksByWeek.6: An obvious favorite to lead the league in total touches, Henry continues to grind out solid fantasy showings with each herculean workload. This week's divisional showdown with Houston looks quite appealing for Henry given the Texans have allowed 5.2 yards per carry to tailbacks, fifth-most in the league. After another two scores in Week 5, Henry is a top option at his position in Week 6.
outlooksByWeek.7: With a career-high 264 scrimmage yards in the overtime win over the Texans this past Sunday, Henry incredibly joined Jim Brown, Barry Sanders and LaDainian Tomlinson as the only players in NFL history with three career games with at least 200 rushing yards and two rushing scores. With an elite Pittsburgh defense coming to town, this game features arguably the league's best rusher against the league's toughest front seven. If any tailback up for such a challenge, it's Henry.
outlooksByWeek.8: It was a solid showing in Week 7 for Henry relative to facing one of the league's best defensive fronts. The performance marked his fourth-straight game with a rushing score. Bound for more than 20 touches, Henry is set to roll this week facing a Bengals defense that recently demoted some key defensive linemen.
outlooksByWeek.9: Delivering his fourth 100-yard game of the season and also tallying a touchdown in the outing, Henry has at least 15 fantasy points in all but one outing this season. Chicago enters this matchup with a defensive reputation, but the Bears have allowed nearly 98 rushing yards per game to backs, supporting another high-end RB1 projection for Henry.
outlooksByWeek.10: Last week's scoreless 68-yard showing is likely what the floor looks like for a healthy Henry. Managers can confidently expect Henry to see over 20 touches against the Colts this week, a defense that has allowed the second-fewest fantasy points per game to backs. Even in a tough matchup, Henry remains a must-start fantasy fixture.
outlooksByWeek.11: The Titans have now lost twice this season when Henry has reached 100 yards, marking the only two such games they've ever lost when he reaches this threshold. Henry looked great on tape in Week 10 and should again overcome a tough matchup to deliver a solid outing this week against the Ravens.
outlooksByWeek.12: Adding to his legend as an early-down force amid a pass-happy NFL climate, Henry just became the first NFL player ever to tally two overtime rushing scores in the same season. Henry also became the third player in franchise history to produce at least 1,000 rushing yards in his first 10 appearances of a season. Proving productive against the Colts a few weeks back, Henry merits trust in all formats this week.
outlooksByWeek.13: This dude might just be good at running the football. For confirmation, we can look to the absurdly productive outing Henry delivered this past Sunday in drubbing the rival Colts, as the pride of Yulee High posted his third career effort with at least 175 yards and three rushing scores, leaving only Hall of Famers Jim Brown (five) and  LaDainian Tomlinson (four) as the only players in history with more such performances. The Browns have been solid against the run this season in allowing the 10th-feewest rushing yards per game to backfields, but Henry is known for defying matchup metrics.
outlooksByWeek.14: An early blowout saw the Titans forced to pass as a means of catching up to Cleveland this past week, leaving Henry with just 15 rush attempts -- his fewest in a game since Week 9 of last season. Henry also uncharacteristically fumbled in the loss, incredibly marking his first fumble in his last 375 touches, ending the longest such active streak in the NFL. The good news for Henry and his fantasy managers is a choice matchup with a Jaguars team allowing roughly 28 fantasy points per game to backs in ESPN PPR leagues, setting up this early-down force for a big game.
outlooksByWeek.15: All Henry did for his fantasy managers was deliver his fourth career game with at least 200 rushing yards and two scores, good for most in NFL history. Looking to become the first player to win back-to-back rushing titles since LaDainian Tomlinson (2006-07), Henry is set to roll all over the Lions this week.
outlooksByWeek.16: Just the fourth player in NFL history with at least 1,500 rushing yards and 15 rushing touchdowns in consecutive seasons, Henry's productivity is remarkable given he's the offensive engine for an NFL offense in a pass-happy era. The Packers have allowed 4.55 yards per carry, aiding Henry's already amazing fantasy profile.
outlooksByWeek.17: Grinding out nearly 100 rushing yards this past week wasn't the big line fantasy investors had hoped for, but for those still playing in Week 17, Henry nets a matchup with a Houston defense allowing the most yards per carry to backs on the year.

player.seasonOutlook: Henry returns as the feature back in Tennessee after pacing the NFL in carries (303), rushing yards (1,540) and rushing touchdowns (16) in 2019. Henry has been an absolute force as a rusher, ranking no lower than third in YAC each of the past three seasons. His heavy recent workload is a concern, but the good news is that he's 25 years old and had not cleared 215 carries in a season prior to 2019. Henry's minimal workload as a receiver (career-high 18 receptions last season) will continue to limit his fantasy output, so coupled with a probable dip in rushing production, he should be valued as a back-end RB1.

outlooksByWeek.1: Hopkins has thrived with varying levels of quality at quarterback in his career. Now he gets the chance to line up alongside a rising star in Kyler Murray. That should be a great opportunity for the veteran out of Clemson.  He gets a perfectly fine matchup against a decent 49ers pass defense (12th-fewest WR points allowed last year) in Week 1. He's a must-start every week, and this is no exception.
outlooksByWeek.2: Hopkins found immediate chemistry with his new QB, Kyler Murray, hauling in an incredible 14 passes against a tough 49ers defense. Expect more of the same in Week 2 against a less-impressive Washington pass defense. Consider Hopkins to be a top-tier option heading into Week 2.
outlooksByWeek.3: Hopkins took a step back in Week 2, "only" scoring one touchdown on nine targets, eight of which were caught. Through two weeks, the former Texans star has at least double the receptions, targets and yards of any other Arizona pass-catcher. He remains the top option in an offense on the rise under second-year passer Kyler Murray. Against a porous Detroit defense, Hopkins is an elite WR1 for Week 3.
outlooksByWeek.4: No player in the NFL has more targets, receptions or yards than Hopkins, who will be a must-start every week this season as long as he's healthy . The touchdowns haven't been there yet, with only one in three games, but that will come around for the veteran wideout. Start him with confidence against Carolina.
outlooksByWeek.5: Hopkins overcame a less-than-ideal injury outlook to play on a team-high 54 snaps in Week 4, but with the Cardinals' passing game gaining only 133 yards in total, his numbers weren't that impressive. Nevertheless, he had nine targets --matching his lowest total in any single game this season, but still very impressive overall. He will face a middle-of-the-pack Jets defense in Week 5. Start him with confidence.
outlooksByWeek.6: Hopkins has alternated 100-yard outings so far this season, with the latest coming on just six receptions, his lowest total of the campaign. That's actually good news for Hopkins, who broke out of a yards-per-catch slump in Week 5 and found the end zone for only the second time this season. His volume makes him a WR1 every week regardless, but his performance against the Jets and a matchup in Week 6 with Dallas makes him a particularly good choice for the week ahead.
outlooksByWeek.7: Hopkins struggled to produce on Monday night thanks in part to Kyler Murray's inaccuracy, but he still saw eight targets and broke out for a 60-yard reception that may have salvaged his week from a fantasy perspective. He's still one of the best wideouts in fantasy, and he'll next face a Seattle defense that's allowing the most WR fantasy points by a fairly wide margin. Hopkins is an elite fantasy option for Week 7.
outlooksByWeek.9: After a bye week to rest his injured ankle, Hopkins should be even better for Week 9 (and beyond) than he has been throughout the first half of the season. His volume is as consistent and impressive as any receiver outside of Davante Adams and Michael Thomas, and he will be a solid WR1 option in all leagues against a good, but not great Miami defense.
outlooksByWeek.10: Hopkins had his worst fantasy output of the season in Week 9, handling only three targets and picking up 30 yards with those three catches. Christian Kirk was the star of the show, and Kyler Murray otherwise spread the ball around, completing a pass to nine different Cardinals. We have no reason to believe this is a long-term change in offensive philosophy but rather just an outlier game for the veteran receiver, and we trust him as a top wideout in Week 10, even against a strong Buffalo pass defense.
outlooksByWeek.11: In what could be the play of the year, Hopkins soared to grab a 43-yard desperation launch from Kyler Murray, using the best hands in the game to secure the ball amid three defenders. For the season, Hopkins' 9.8 YPT is on pace to set a new career-high. Hopkins has a chance to improve on that mark even more as the Cardinals take on the Seahawks and the league's worst pass defense in Week 11's Thursday night affair.
outlooksByWeek.12: In Week 11, Hopkins had one of the more disappointing outings of the season from a fantasy perspective, failing to post big numbers against a Seattle team allowing the most WR fantasy points per game. It's hard to imagine him remaining in a slump for long, though, and against a more average New England defense, it's time to expect a rebound outing. Lock in Hopkins as your WR1.
outlooksByWeek.13: Hopkins has slowed down (along with the rest of the Arizona offense), but there's no reason to give up on the star wideout. The Rams do offer one of the toughest WR matchups in football, allowing the fewest fantasy points per game to the position. Still, with seven-plus targets in all but one game this season, Hopkins is a must-start in all leagues regardless of opponent.
outlooksByWeek.14: Hopkins has finished with between 51-55 yards receiving for three straight games now -- a byproduct of an Arizona passing game that has lost some explosiveness as Kyler Murray has faced tougher matchups and is potentially dealing with a lingering shoulder injury. Either way, Hopkins is still a red-zone threat and a consistent target all over the field. He gets more than enough volume to stay in your lineup against a mediocre Giants secondary.
outlooksByWeek.15: In Week 14, Hopkins rewarded those who stuck with the superstar receiver, breaking out for more than 100 yards against the Giants. His stats have been trending up in recent weeks and, with his best matchup in a long while this week against a Philadelphia secondary that struggles to handle receivers, he's an easy choice to utilize as a WR1 in all formats.
outlooksByWeek.16: Hopkins has been thriving in recent weeks with Kyler Murray looking closer to 100%. He has seen double-digit targets in three straight contests and posted a dominant performance last week against the Eagles. The first time Hopkins faced the 49ers this season, he ran wild for 151 yards. Even though San Francisco has solid defensive metrics, there's no reason to move Hopkins out of your starting lineup for this one.
outlooksByWeek.17: Both Hopkins and his quarterback, Kyler Murray, will be fighting off injuries as they prepare for a must-win matchup in Week 17 against a stalwart Rams defense. If you have Hopkins, he has to be in your lineup, since he has seen 10-plus targets in each of the last four games. That said, his upside might be limited thanks to the tough matchup and the injuries with which he and his teammates are currently dealing.

player.seasonOutlook: Hopkins was traded to the Cardinals during the offseason and will now operate as Kyler Murray's go-to target. A top-five fantasy WR in four of the past five seasons, Hopkins has averaged 10.5 targets per game during that span, which is a mark he should still be able to approach with Arizona. Murray is far from a finished product, but the Cardinals' offense finished 2019 strong with three-plus touchdowns in eight of their final 11 games -- and that was without one of the game's best receivers. At age 28, Hopkins remains an elite fantasy option and should be selected near the first/second-round turn.

outlooksByWeek.1: From undrafted receiver to breakout tight end, Waller thrived as a steady target of Derek Carr last season. While he's unlikely to approach his awesome target clip last season, Waller should remain a fine fantasy starter heading into a matchup with a Carolina defense missing legendary cover linebacker Luke Kuechly.
outlooksByWeek.2: Even if his stat line looked a bit light, Waller still led the team in routes and targets against the Panthers. One of the rare full-time tight ends in the league, Waller will be plenty busy working against the Saints' exploitable back seven.
outlooksByWeek.3: An awesomely productive Week 2 was fueled by a career-best 16 targets. We don't expect such amazing opportunity rates for this matchup with the Patriots, but it does help Waller's case that double-digit target shares are always within reach.
outlooksByWeek.4: Limited to a quiet outing with just two catches for nine yards this past week with the Patriots focusing on Waller, it's worth remembering he led the Raiders with 18 catches for 150 yards over the first two games. Due for a stronger showing against the Bills this week, Waller remains firmly in the TE1 mix.
outlooksByWeek.5: Back to his target-rich role around the line of scrimmage with 11 targets, albeit on just five air yards per target, Waller was relatively stellar in Week 4. The Chiefs have been really solid in pass coverage this season, but Waller's volume-driven role merits trust in all formats.
outlooksByWeek.7: With twice as many receptions as any of his teammates, Waller is the clear top target on an underrated Las Vegas passing offense. This week offers a unique challenge given that Tampa Bay is one of the tougher pass defenses in the league, but Waller's awesome target share keep him in the starting mix.
outlooksByWeek.8: A touchdown and 25% share of targets last week cemented another solid week of usage and productionfor Waller. Arguably the only bankable receiving threat each week from this offense, Waller is in a good spot against a Cleveland defense that has struggled in coverage this season.
outlooksByWeek.9: The most bankable and projectable receiver on the Raiders each week, Waller could feast on a Chargers back seven that has allowed the 10th-most fantasy points per game to tight ends. Given this blend of positive matchup and usage data, Waller is among the top plays at his position this week.
outlooksByWeek.10: The most bankable skill player on the Raiders this season, Waller salvaged an inefficient Week 9 with a visit to the end zone. The rival Broncos are up next and while Denver has proven respectable in covering tight ends, awesome target volume and a rewarding red zone role continue to drive TE1 expectations for Waller.
outlooksByWeek.11: The Raiders ran away from the pass last week in order to run. That is a messy sentence, but the premise being Waller wasn't fed much work last week because the team simply didn't need to. This week, Waller should be plenty busy as a key target for Derek Carr against the rival Chiefs.
outlooksByWeek.12: Averaging more targets per game than in his breakout 2019 effort and with a sizable leap in touchdown rate thus far, Waller is proving last season's opus was indeed a trend and not an outlier. A productive seven-reception showing in a riveting showdown with the Chiefs in Week 11 has Waller on pace for a career-high 96 catches. Next up is a fun matchup with Atlanta.
outlooksByWeek.13: This past week against the Falcons might just be a throwaway game in that Derek Carr was off from the start and the Falcons defense was surprisingly relentless. This all led to Waller producing his second-lowest fantasy tally of the year. Thankfully, a softer matchup awaits with the Jets allowing 14.6 fantasy points per game to tight ends, right around Waller's strong projection this week.
outlooksByWeek.14: It's possible the Jets forgot that Waller is really good or that he was even on the field, as the Raiders' top target went off for a career outing that included a whopping 200 yards -- a tally good for the sixth-most ever in a game for a tight end. The Colts have been generally great against the pass this season, but Waller's unique usage elevates him to must-start status for Week 14.
outlooksByWeek.15: A weekly force at the position, Waller is the No. 2 fantasy option at tight this season and should be in lineups every week even when facing a respectable crew of safeties like the Chargers claim.
outlooksByWeek.16: Waller is a baller. We just came up with that. In another awesome outing, Waller produced at least 150 receiving yards for the second time this year and became just the fourth tight end with multiple such performances in a season in the Super Bowl era. The Dolphins have a ball-hawking secondary, but Waller is clearly a must-start option.
outlooksByWeek.17: An awesome finish to the season has helped Waller deliver his second straight 1,000-yard campaign, as he joins Todd Christensen as the only Raiders tight ends with multiple seasons in the 1K club. The Broncos limited Waller to a sluggish game earlier this year, but his undeniable momentum keeps him as a top play this week.

player.seasonOutlook: Waller's breakout 2019 season marked one of the most improbable breakout campaigns you'll ever see. Waller was drafted in the sixth round of the 2015 draft as a 6-foot-6 wide receiver. He barely saw the field while dealing with addiction but got back on his feet as a tight end with the Raiders. An absolute force from the get-go, Waller finished no lower than fourth among tight ends in snaps, routes, targets, receptions, yardage or YPT. Waller was held to three touchdowns (3.9 OTD) but finished third in fantasy points. The 27-year-old is Derek Carr's top target and positioned well for another high-volume season. He's a top-five fantasy tight end.

outlooksByWeek.1: Last season, Kamara couldn't repeat his incredible 18-TD performance from 2018 -- and injuries certainly played their part. That said, he was always due for a bit of regression in the scoring department. He still managed a healthy 18 points per game and hopes to be healthy heading into Week 1 against the Buccaneers, who were strong against the run but not against the pass in 2019. Since Kamara can make things happen in both phases of the game, he's still a solid RB1 option in fantasy.
outlooksByWeek.2: A pair of scores -- one on the ground and the other in the air -- salvaged an otherwise blas opener for Kamara as he averaged a paltry 1.3 yards on 12 carries to go along with five catches for 51 yards against an improving Tampa Bay defense. Kamara should be more productive in Week 2 as he draws a more generous Raiders unit. As always, feel free to start your fantasy first rounder with confidence.
outlooksByWeek.3: Kamara was the chief beneficiary of Michael Thomas' absence on Monday night with 22 touches for 174 yards-from-scrimmage and a pair of rushing touchdowns. Kamara was especially productive as a receiver and is in a good spot to do so again against Green Bay in Week 3. Kamara is matchup-proof with a good chance to be the No. 1 overall running back in Week 3.
outlooksByWeek.4: Through three weeks, Kamara leads all running backs in yards from scrimmage (438), receptions (27) and touchdowns (6). Kamara usually does most of his damage running routes out of the backfield, but since the Lions have allowed the third-most RB rushing yards, he may enjoy a better game as a ball carrier. Nevertheless, at the end of Week 4, Kamara should keep his place as the top fantasy running back over the first quarter of the season.
outlooksByWeek.5: You know the bar is set pretty high when 23 touches accounting for 119 yards from scrimmage and a rushing touchdown is "just another day." Kamara's effort helped keep him as the RB fantasy points leader. Kamara is in line for a big day coming out of the backfield in Week 5 as the Chargers have allowed the fourth-most RB receptions this season, with two going for scores.
outlooksByWeek.7: Kamara comes out of the Saints' Week 6 bye looking to fortify his spot as the top fantasy running back in the game. A date with the Tampa Bay defense usually spells trouble as the Buccaneers allow a league-low 49 yards per game on the ground to running backs. On the other hand, they're soft against pass-catching backs, which plays into Kamara's strength. You made it through his bye, so don't forget to click Kamara back into your Week 7 lineup.
outlooksByWeek.8: With the Saints missing both Michael Thomas and Emmanuel Sanders in Week 7 against the Panthers, Kamara's already heavy workload was expected to increase. With those two high-profile teammates sidelined, Carolina could key more on Kamara, but it didn't faze him. Fantasy's top back ran 14 times for 83 yards along with capturing all eight of his targets for 65 more yards. Kamara will again be the focal point this week against the Bears. Even if Thomas and Sanders both return, count on Kamara for another big effort.
outlooksByWeek.9: With the Saints missing receivers Michael Thomas, Emmanuel Sanders and Marquez Callaway in Week 8, their offense needed Kamara to contribute even more in the passing game. He delivered by securing 9-of-13 targets for 96 yards in addition to grinding out 67 yards on the ground with a dozen carries. Week 9 presents a stiff challenge with New Orleans heading to Tampa Bay for a rematch of their Week 1 clash. That said, Kamara is obviously matchup-proof.
outlooksByWeek.10: Game flow hindered Kamara's workload in the Saints surprisingly easy 38-3 shellacking of the Buccaneers in the Week 9 Sunday night showcase. Kamara still managed 40 yards on nine rushes including a score along with an unusually low five catches for just nine yards. Look for Kamara to return to a larger workload as the Saints take on the 49ers in Week 10.
outlooksByWeek.11: In Week 10, the 49ers' run defense contained Kamara as he was only able to muster 15 yards on the ground, although two of his carries were short end-zone plunges. Kamara was his usual effective self as a receiver, catching seven balls for 83 yards and a third score. Even without Drew Brees at quarterback in Week 11, Kamara remains a top fantasy option, with New Orleans facing the porous Falcons defense.
outlooksByWeek.12: For the second time in three weeks, Kamara failed to surpass 50 yards from scrimmage as his production was limited to 45 rushing yards on 13 carries, though he did find the end zone. With another week to try and develop some chemistry with replacement-QB Taysom Hill, Kamara's usually heavy involvement in the passing game could return. He's still an obvious start when the Saints travel to Denver for their Week 12 tilt, but it will be interesting to monitor Kamara's usage.
outlooksByWeek.13: For the second straight week with Taysom Hill at the helm, Kamara was absent from the Saints' passing game, but at least there was a reason for the dearth of targets in Week 12. New Orleans was ahead the whole game and never in danger of losing to Denver. Kamara did run for 54 yards on 11 carries in the lopsided affair. While it's fair to be concerned about the recent trend, Kamara should be more involved in Week 13, with a prime matchup against the Falcons' generous defense.
outlooksByWeek.14: Kamara entered Week 13's contest with only one reception in the two games with Taysom Hill at the helm. While he only caught two more balls in the Saints' victory over Atlanta, he did ramble for 88 rushing yards on 15 carries, including an impressive 37-yarder and an 11-yard TD burst. Kamara's involvement in the passing game is likely to remain low until Drew Brees returns (possibly in Week 14), but he's still an automatic start regardless of who is taking those QB snaps.
outlooksByWeek.15: Kamara's presence in the Saints' passing game returned in Week 14 as he caught 7-of-10 targets for 44 yards on top of a productive day on the ground (11 rushes for 50 yards and a score). The Saints will be looking to bounce back from their 24-21 loss in Philadelphia when they entertain the Chiefs in one of Week 15's top matchups. Kamara should be in line for another big day in what could be a high-scoring affair.
outlooksByWeek.16: With Drew Brees back at the Week 15 helm, Kamara rushed 11 times for 54 yards and also caught three balls for 40 yards -- including his first scoring strike since Week 10. As always, Kamara is one of the top options in Week 16 as the Saints host the Vikings on Friday.
outlooksByWeek.17: So, what is he going to do for an encore? Kamara obviously won't repeat his historic Week 16 effort, but he's in a good spot for a typically solid performance with the Saints still firmly in the running for the NFC's best record. Carolina's defense has allowed the eighth-most RB fantasy points per game this season.

player.seasonOutlook: Kamara is coming off an up-and-down 2019 campaign, but the 24-year-old remains the main man in the New Orleans' backfield. Kamara missed a pair of games but otherwise played a similar role to 2018, handling 12.2 carries and 7.0 targets per game. Kamara ended the season with a YPC above 4.5 and exactly 81 catches for the third consecutive season. A lack of usage near the goal line (7.1 OTD, 6 TDs) limited his fantasy production, though he did finish strongly with four of those scores coming during Weeks 16-17. Kamara should have little trouble pushing for 20 touches per game in the Saints' Drew Brees-led, high-scoring offense. He remains a solid RB1.
